Pantheon Semantic Coordinate Layer (PSCL) v0.1

Subtitle: Language-native embedding surrogate for doctrine, memory, and cross-domain transfer

1. Purpose

The Pantheon Semantic Coordinate Layer defines a structured, legible alternative to opaque embedding vectors.

Its goal is to let Pantheon concepts be stored, compared, retrieved, and transformed as explicit semantic objects rather than only prose. Conversation remains the interface, but meaning is stabilized underneath as a graph of invariants, relations, and transfer rules.

This gives Pantheon an embedding-like substrate without requiring direct access to model-internal vectors.

⸻

2. Design Claim

A true embedding is useful because it places meaning in a space where:
	•	similarity is measurable
	•	neighborhoods exist
	•	analogies can be traversed
	•	concepts can be retrieved by relation rather than exact wording

PSCL reproduces those functions through explicit structure:
	•	nodes instead of hidden vectors
	•	relations instead of latent distances
	•	invariants instead of compressed black-box features
	•	transforms instead of implicit analogies
	•	weights/tags instead of uninterpretable dimensions

This is slower than native embeddings, but more legible, auditable, and doctrine-compatible.

⸻

3. Core Objects

3.1 Semantic Node

A Semantic Node is the canonical unit of meaning.

Each node represents one concept, pattern, daemon, invariant, protocol, or operational insight.

Required fields

id: string
name: string
type: concept | daemon | invariant | protocol | pattern | field | metric
summary: string
core_invariant: string
compression_phrase: string
domains: [string]
neighbors: [string]
failure_modes: [string]
transfers: [string]
safety_constraints: [string]

Optional fields

aliases: [string]
opposites: [string]
examples: [string]
source_threads: [string]
related_doctrines: [string]
spectral_tags:
  salience: low | medium | high
  rigidity: low | medium | high
  abstraction: low | medium | high
  risk: low | medium | high
  reversibility: low | medium | high
status: draft | canonical | deprecated | fossil
version: string


⸻

3.2 Semantic Edge

An edge defines a relationship between two nodes.

from: string
to: string
relation: supports | opposes | refines | generalizes | instantiates | maps_to | predicts | guards | compresses | rehydrates
weight: float   # 0.0 - 1.0
notes: string


⸻

3.3 Transfer Rule

A Transfer Rule describes how a concept moves across substrates.

id: string
source_domain: string
target_domain: string
preserved_invariant: string
mapping_rule: string
break_conditions: [string]
example: string

Example:

id: pain_to_ai_feedback
source_domain: biology
target_domain: ai-governance
preserved_invariant: negative feedback prevents silent failure
mapping_rule: pain -> error signal, relief -> reward, injury risk -> invariant breach
break_conditions:
  - anthropomorphic interpretation
  - loss of measurable threshold
example: biological pain maps to Pantheon error delta thresholds


